I have everything I need for a complete diagnosis. Here is the full breakdown.

---

## Diagnosis

The active/drag highlight label appears to the **right** of the rail, extending off the right viewport edge, instead of joining the hover-label stack on the left of the rail.

### What you tried (and why it was a no-op)

Switching the `getBoundingClientRect()` anchor from the inner `<button class={styles.tick}>` to the outer `<div data-notch-index={i} class={styles.notch}>` changes `r.left` by the width difference between the notch and the tick — a few pixels at most. Both elements are right-aligned inside the same 28 px `.notch` container, so both return a `left` value that is the **right-side edge of the content column minus 28 px** — essentially the same X position. The underlying coordinate model was never corrected.

---

## Root Cause (AP-069 — Portaled-element coordinate-space mismatch)

The anchor `<div>` is portaled to `<body>` and positioned with:

```scss
// ScrollSpy.module.scss
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
  …
}
```

`translate(-100%, …)` on a `position: fixed` element shifts by **the element's own rendered width** — the text width of the label. The inline style then sets:

```tsx
left: `${overlayPos.left}px`   // r.left  ≈ viewport.right − 28 px
```

`r.left` is the **left** edge of the notch. Because the `.rail` is `position: fixed; right: $portfolio-spacing-05`, the notch's left edge is near the right side of the viewport. Setting `left` to that value, then applying `translate(-100%)` only subtracts the label's own text-width — the label still ends up sitting **to the right of the rail gutter**, flush against the right viewport edge.

The in-rail hover labels achieve correct placement because they are `position: absolute` children of `.notch` and use:

```scss
.label {
  right: calc(100% + #{$portfolio-spacing-03});
  …
}
```

`right: 100%` here means *"my right edge is at the parent notch's left edge"* — that is the shared gutter line. The portaled label needs to replicate that same geometric contract: its **right edge** must land exactly at the notch's left edge. Using `left = r.left` and `translate(-100%)` only happens to work when the text width exactly equals the gap between `r.left` and the gutter, which it never does. The correct anchor coordinate is **`r.left`** used as the `right` CSS property — not `left`.

---

## Fix

Two changes: one in `ScrollSpy.tsx` (store `right` from the viewport calculation), one in `ScrollSpy.module.scss` (use `right` instead of `left`, and simplify the transform).

### `src/components/ScrollSpy.tsx`

```tsx
// BEFORE — overlayPos stores `left`
const [overlayPos, setOverlayPos] = useState<{
  top: number;
  left: number;
} | null>(null);

// …inside compute():
const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
setOverlayPos({
  top: r.top + r.height / 2,
  left: r.left,            // ← left edge of notch, used as CSS `left`
});

// …in the portal JSX:
style={
  overlayPos
    ? {
        top: `${overlayPos.top}px`,
        left: `${overlayPos.left}px`,   // ← wrong axis
      }
    : { top: 0, left: 0, visibility: "hidden" }
}
```

```tsx
// AFTER — overlayPos stores `right` (distance from viewport right edge)
const [overlayPos, setOverlayPos] = useState<{
  top: number;
  right: number;            // ← renamed: viewport.width − notch.left
} | null>(null);

// …inside compute():
const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
setOverlayPos({
  top:  r.top + r.height / 2,
  right: window.innerWidth - r.left,  // ← notch left edge as a `right` offset
});

// …in the portal JSX:
style={
  overlayPos
    ? {
        top:   `${overlayPos.top}px`,
        right: `${overlayPos.right}px`,   // ← correct axis
      }
    : { top: 0, right: 0, visibility: "hidden" }
}
```

Full updated `ScrollSpy.tsx`:

```tsx
"use client";

import {
  useEffect,
  useLayoutEffect,
  useRef,
  useState,
  useCallback,
} from "react";
import { createPortal } from "react-dom";
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from "framer-motion";
import { DURATION, EASING } from "@/lib/motion";
import styles from "./ScrollSpy.module.scss";

const useIsomorphicLayoutEffect =
  typeof window !== "undefined" ? useLayoutEffect : useEffect;

export type ScrollSpySection = {
  id: string;
  label: string;
  depth?: 0 | 1;
  group?: string;
};

type ScrollSpyProps = {
  sections: ScrollSpySection[];
};

export default function ScrollSpy({ sections }: ScrollSpyProps) {
  const [activeIndex, setActiveIndex]   = useState(0);
  const [isHovered, setIsHovered]       = useState(false);
  const [dragIndex, setDragIndex]       = useState<number | null>(null);
  const [mounted, setMounted]           = useState(false);
  const [overlayPos, setOverlayPos]     = useState<{
    top: number;
    right: number;   // distance from viewport right edge to the notch's left edge
  } | null>(null);

  const trackRef      = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);
  const drag          = useRef({ active: false, index: -1 });
  const pointerStart  = useRef<{ y: number; index: number } | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => setMounted(true), []);

  useEffect(() => {
    const elements = sections
      .map((s) => document.getElementById(s.id))
      .filter(Boolean) as HTMLElement[];

    if (elements.length === 0) return;

    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
      (entries) => {
        if (drag.current.active) return;

        let best: IntersectionObserverEntry | null = null;
        for (const entry of entries) {
          if (!entry.isIntersecting) continue;
          if (
            !best ||
            entry.boundingClientRect.top < best.boundingClientRect.top
          ) {
            best = entry;
          }
        }

        if (best) {
          const idx = elements.indexOf(best.target as HTMLElement);
          if (idx !== -1) setActiveIndex(idx);
        }
      },
      { rootMargin: "-20% 0px -60% 0px", threshold: 0 },
    );

    elements.forEach((el) => observer.observe(el));
    return () => observer.disconnect();
  }, [sections]);

  const scrollTo = useCallback(
    (index: number, behavior: ScrollBehavior = "smooth") => {
      const el = document.getElementById(sections[index]?.id);
      if (el) {
        const top =
          el.getBoundingClientRect().top +
          window.scrollY -
          window.innerHeight * 0.2;
        window.scrollTo({ top: Math.max(0, top), behavior });
        setActiveIndex(index);
      }
    },
    [sections],
  );

  const indexFromPointer = useCallback((clientY: number): number => {
    const notches =
      trackRef.current?.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>("[data-notch-index]");
    if (!notches || notches.length === 0) return 0;
    let closest = 0;
    let minDist  = Infinity;
    notches.forEach((el, i) => {
      const rect = el.getBoundingClientRect();
      const dist = Math.abs(clientY - (rect.top + rect.height / 2));
      if (dist < minDist) {
        minDist  = dist;
        closest  = i;
      }
    });
    return closest;
  }, []);

  const onPointerDown = useCallback(
    (e: React.PointerEvent) => {
      if (e.button !== 0) return;
      e.preventDefault();
      trackRef.current?.setPointerCapture(e.pointerId);
      const idx = indexFromPointer(e.clientY);
      pointerStart.current = { y: e.clientY, index: idx };
    },
    [indexFromPointer],
  );

  const onPointerMove = useCallback(
    (e: React.PointerEvent) => {
      if (!pointerStart.current) return;

      if (!drag.current.active) {
        if (Math.abs(e.clientY - pointerStart.current.y) < 3) return;
        drag.current = { active: true, index: pointerStart.current.index };
        setDragIndex(pointerStart.current.index);
        scrollTo(pointerStart.current.index, "instant");
      }

      const idx = indexFromPointer(e.clientY);
      if (idx !== drag.current.index) {
        drag.current.index = idx;
        setDragIndex(idx);
        scrollTo(idx, "instant");
      }
    },
    [indexFromPointer, scrollTo],
  );

  const endInteraction = useCallback(() => {
    if (pointerStart.current && !drag.current.active) {
      scrollTo(pointerStart.current.index, "smooth");
    }
    drag.current  = { active: false, index: -1 };
    pointerStart.current = null;
    setDragIndex(null);
  }, [scrollTo]);

  const isDragging       = dragIndex !== null;
  const highlightIndex   = isDragging ? dragIndex : activeIndex;
  const highlightVisible = isDragging ? dragIndex !== null : isHovered;
  const highlightSection = highlightIndex != null ? sections[highlightIndex] : undefined;
  const highlightDepth   = highlightSection?.depth ?? 0;

  useIsomorphicLayoutEffect(() => {
    if (!mounted || !highlightVisible || highlightIndex == null) {
      setOverlayPos(null);
      return;
    }

    const compute = () => {
      const notch = trackRef.current?.querySelector<HTMLElement>(
        `[data-notch-index="${highlightIndex}"]`,
      );
      if (!notch) {
        setOverlayPos(null);
        return;
      }
      const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
      setOverlayPos({
        top:   r.top + r.height / 2,
        // Convert the notch's left edge to a `right` CSS value so the
        // anchor's right edge snaps to exactly the same gutter line that
        // in-rail .label elements use (`right: calc(100% + spacer)` on the
        // notch). Using `left: r.left` with `translate(-100%)` only
        // subtracts the label's own text-width and leaves the label
        // stranded at the viewport's right edge. AP-069.
        right: window.innerWidth - r.left,
      });
    };

    compute();
    window.addEventListener("resize", compute);
    window.addEventListener("scroll", compute, true);
    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener("resize", compute);
      window.removeEventListener("scroll", compute, true);
    };
  }, [mounted, highlightVisible, highlightIndex]);

  if (sections.length < 2) return null;

  return (
    <>
      <nav className={styles.rail} aria-label="Page sections">
        <div
          ref={trackRef}
          className={styles.track}
          data-hovered={isHovered || undefined}
          data-dragging={isDragging || undefined}
          onPointerEnter={() => setIsHovered(true)}
          onPointerLeave={() => setIsHovered(false)}
          onPointerDown={onPointerDown}
          onPointerMove={onPointerMove}
          onPointerUp={endInteraction}
          onLostPointerCapture={endInteraction}
        >
          {sections.map((section, i) => {
            const isActive     = i === activeIndex;
            const isDragTarget = isDragging && i === dragIndex;
            const showLabel    = isDragging ? isDragTarget : isHovered;
            const isHighlight  = i === highlightIndex;
            const depth        = section.depth ?? 0;

            return (
              <div
                key={section.id}
                className={styles.notch}
                data-notch-index={i}
                data-active={isActive || undefined}
                data-depth={depth || undefined}
              >
                <AnimatePresence>
                  {showLabel && !isHighlight && (
                    <motion.span
                      className={styles.label}
                      initial={{ opacity: 0, x: 4 }}
                      animate={{ opacity: 1, x: 0 }}
                      exit={{ opacity: 0, x: 4 }}
                      transition={{
                        duration: isDragging ? 0 : DURATION.fast,
                        ease: EASING.standard,
                      }}
                    >
                      {section.label}
                    </motion.span>
                  )}
                </AnimatePresence>

                <button
                  className={styles.tick}
                  data-active={isActive || undefined}
                  data-drag-target={isDragTarget || undefined}
                  data-depth={depth || undefined}
                  onClick={() => scrollTo(i)}
                  aria-label={`Jump to ${section.label}`}
                  aria-current={isActive ? "true" : undefined}
                />
              </div>
            );
          })}
        </div>
      </nav>

      {mounted &&
        highlightSection &&
        createPortal(
          <div
            className={styles.highlightLabelAnchor}
            style={
              overlayPos
                ? {
                    top:   `${overlayPos.top}px`,
                    right: `${overlayPos.right}px`,   // ← was `left`
                  }
                : { top: 0, right: 0, visibility: "hidden" }
            }
            aria-hidden="true"
          >
            <motion.span
              className={styles.highlightLabel}
              data-depth={highlightDepth || undefined}
              initial={false}
              animate={{
                opacity: highlightVisible && overlayPos ? 1 : 0,
                x: highlightVisible && overlayPos ? 0 : 4,
              }}
              transition={{
                duration: isDragging ? 0 : DURATION.fast,
                ease: EASING.standard,
              }}
            >
              {highlightSection.label}
            </motion.span>
          </div>,
          document.body,
        )}
    </>
  );
}
```

### `src/components/ScrollSpy.module.scss`

```scss
// BEFORE
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
  color: #fff;
  mix-blend-mode: difference;
  z-index: 41;
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: top, left;
}
```

```scss
// AFTER
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  // `right` is now set inline as `window.innerWidth − notch.left`.
  // The anchor's right edge is therefore exactly at the notch's left edge —
  // the same gutter line used by in-rail .label elements.
  // Only a vertical centering transform remains; no horizontal translate needed.
  transform: translateY(-50%);
  color: #fff;
  mix-blend-mode: difference;
  z-index: 41;
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: top, right;    // ← was `top, left`
}
```

---

## Why this is correct — geometric proof

| Element | Gutter definition |
|---|---|
| `.label` (in-rail) | `position: absolute; right: calc(100% + spacer)` on `.notch` → right edge of label = left edge of notch |
| `.highlightLabelAnchor` (portaled, **before**) | `position: fixed; left: notch.left; transform: translate(-100% - spacer)` → right edge = `notch.left − labelWidth − spacer` — **off by `labelWidth`** |
| `.highlightLabelAnchor` (portaled, **after**) | `position: fixed; right: (viewport.width − notch.left)` → right edge = `viewport.width − (viewport.width − notch.left)` = `notch.left` ✓ |

With `right` set to `viewport.width − notch.left`, the anchor's **right edge pins exactly to the notch's left edge**, which is the definition of the gutter. No additional horizontal transform is needed, eliminating the dependency on the label's rendered text width that made the original formula wrong.

---

## Principle

**AP-069 — Portaled-element coordinate-space mismatch.** When a portal escapes a stacking context, inline styles must use the coordinate *axis* that matches the desired alignment gutter, not the mirrored one. A right-aligned rail gutter is most naturally expressed as a `right` offset from the viewport edge; translating a `left` coordinate by the element's own `width` produces correct output only in the degenerate case where `width === 0`. Always derive the `right` CSS value as `window.innerWidth − boundingClientRect.left` rather than fighting the transform chain.
